1
00:00:01,280 --> 00:00:08,128
Now what I want to do this evening is just explain the theory behind the practice you're doing so that you feel a bit more confident about it.

2
00:00:10,351 --> 00:00:28,231
The Mahasi Sayadaw was a monk living in the north of Burma who must have got himself a good name for teaching meditation because it was people in Rangoon

3
00:00:28,381 --> 00:00:34,587
which is in the south, well, in the middle of Burma, who went looking for a teacher after the war.

4
00:00:35,768 --> 00:00:36,588
Generals, actually.

5
00:00:37,070 --> 00:00:37,670
A couple of them were.

6
00:00:40,313 --> 00:00:43,936
And they asked him to come down and begin teaching.

7
00:00:45,838 --> 00:00:50,362
And I think to everybody's surprise, it sort of took off.

8
00:00:50,383 --> 00:00:54,826
Up until he began teaching, although they'd been...

9
00:00:56,140 --> 00:01:00,328
a small resurgence of Vipassana meditation in the early century.

10
00:01:01,409 --> 00:01:05,959
By the time he began, it really wasn't something that lay people did.

11
00:01:05,978 --> 00:01:09,504
I don't think it was what monks did either.

12
00:01:11,289 --> 00:01:18,822
Monks tended to practice a form of meditation known as Samatha, which is basically just being peaceful.

13
00:01:19,664 --> 00:01:26,813
being calm, using the breath just to be calm but not for purposes of trying to understand or trying to have insight.

14
00:01:29,195 --> 00:01:34,022
So it was really quite a new venture and as I say it really took off.

15
00:01:35,403 --> 00:01:48,000
So much so that by the mid-fifties he was actually traveling and he went to Sri Lanka, set up centers there and it was at one of those centers that I spent so many years

16
00:01:48,706 --> 00:01:54,495
And then he eventually came to Britain, did a tour of Britain, used to be a centre over in Oxford.

17
00:01:55,496 --> 00:02:08,959
And that's where I first contacted this particular form through one of his protégés, Sayadaw Ujanaka, who's still living and has a centre in Rangoon, and later his other protégé, Upandita.

18
00:02:10,812 --> 00:02:15,576
And some of you may know, for instance, people like Joseph Goldstein, he's pretty famous.

19
00:02:16,276 --> 00:02:19,120
So he sort of teaches this particular system.

20
00:02:21,021 --> 00:02:35,757
So it's taught around the world, really, and we're pretty lucky in Britain now because they're opening a center in Manchester, the monks who come from Upandita's line.

21
00:02:36,461 --> 00:02:40,651
So there'll be a fundamentalist center in Manchester.

22
00:02:43,395 --> 00:02:57,525
So what he did was present a system of investigation supported by techniques so that there wasn't a moment in the day when you were let off.

23
00:02:58,197 --> 00:03:02,805
when you could relax, in a sense, into a sort of dozy, peaceful state.

24
00:03:03,385 --> 00:03:14,907
You had to, as it were, make a real effort to develop this quality of just watching with a sharp or an attentive curiosity, a wanting to know.

25
00:03:15,712 --> 00:03:19,881
Remember, it's this wanting to know which is specific to the Gnostic path.

26
00:03:20,081 --> 00:03:36,895
Gnostic here meaning the path that leads to a spiritual awakening by way of investigation, rather than, shall we say, a path that might lead there through developing love, a more devotional path, a bhakti path.

27
00:03:39,018 --> 00:03:56,570
So all these techniques that we're doing are really there just to awaken this pure intelligence within us, this intuitive intelligence that can directly experience things before words.

28
00:03:56,938 --> 00:04:03,251
And concepts interfere before emotions distort what we're actually looking at, prejudice.

29
00:04:03,991 --> 00:04:14,390
So, first of all, in the sitting posture, there's this noting technique.

30
00:04:15,534 --> 00:04:20,201
So one thing this intelligence has to do is go beyond the word.

31
00:04:20,922 --> 00:04:23,245
So the question is, why do we use a word anyway?

32
00:04:24,086 --> 00:04:31,074
So obviously the technique, what it does when you present one word, is at least it stops the mind from wandering.

33
00:04:31,314 --> 00:04:34,860
At least it stops the mind thinking about something.

34
00:04:35,954 --> 00:04:44,403
So we're going right back to that sort of slightly pre-verbal stage when, for instance, a child might see something and just shout, car, car.

35
00:04:44,925 --> 00:04:46,987
But the word car has very little meaning.

36
00:04:47,367 --> 00:04:49,730
It doesn't have a desire to have a car.

37
00:04:49,790 --> 00:04:54,516
It doesn't have all the experiences that we get going around in a car.

38
00:04:55,197 --> 00:04:56,399
It's just a car.

39
00:04:56,459 --> 00:04:57,540
It's just an object.

40
00:04:58,312 --> 00:04:58,612
You see?

41
00:04:59,053 --> 00:05:03,100
And it's that clarity of just noting that we want to get down to.

42
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:08,990
And the clarity comes because the noting word is restricting the thinking mind.

43
00:05:09,410 --> 00:05:13,475
So, okay, there's a concept there, but at least it's a simple concept.

44
00:05:15,199 --> 00:05:16,180
Just a word, you see?

45
00:05:16,762 --> 00:05:17,723
Rising.

46
00:05:18,478 --> 00:05:18,879
Falling.

47
00:05:19,459 --> 00:05:35,137
Now I say in this particular tape, I mean to change it for my next edition, that you go rising, falling, and in the break between the out-breath and the in-breath, you sort of see the whole feeling body, as it were.

48
00:05:35,358 --> 00:05:41,345
And I give this image of a bird in a tree, and then as it were, you see the whole tree because the bird's not moving.

49
00:05:41,504 --> 00:05:43,848
You don't have to specifically look at the bird, as it were.

50
00:05:44,247 --> 00:05:47,372
But as soon as the bird moves, your eye catches it.

51
00:05:48,937 --> 00:05:51,300
So some people find this a little bit difficult.

52
00:05:51,701 --> 00:05:56,387
So the other thing you can do is simply go to a touch point.

53
00:05:56,708 --> 00:06:05,158
So rising, falling, and then if you feel, for instance, your ankles on the floor or your knees or your hands, so you just go to that point.

54
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:09,684
The reason for that is just to keep the thinking mind occupied.

55
00:06:10,125 --> 00:06:13,408
If you don't occupy it, it'll occupy itself and off it'll go somewhere.

56
00:06:15,290 --> 00:06:15,992
Acapulco.

57
00:06:17,204 --> 00:06:19,690
Who wants to go to Acapulco in the middle of London?

58
00:06:20,935 --> 00:06:30,201
So by maintaining that word, you see, you're actually containing the thinking mind and constantly aiming it at the object.

59
00:06:38,821 --> 00:06:42,607
Now some people in their meditation don't get this break after the out-breath.

60
00:06:43,247 --> 00:06:44,588
In which case, forget it, you see.

61
00:06:44,850 --> 00:06:46,892
Just go rising, falling, rising, falling.

62
00:06:47,173 --> 00:06:50,237
Don't create a break if there's not one there.

63
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:54,744
Usually it's because of tension, you see.

64
00:06:56,226 --> 00:07:00,593
A person who doesn't have that break actually is slightly hyperventilating.

65
00:07:02,529 --> 00:07:03,271
This is the truth.

66
00:07:03,591 --> 00:07:06,074
So, it'll come as you relax.

67
00:07:06,435 --> 00:07:08,858
Because, you know, the breath just stops and then there's the relaxation.

68
00:07:09,137 --> 00:07:13,504
Then the in-breath comes.

69
00:07:13,524 --> 00:07:17,829
So, that's the noting as it comes to the breath.

70
00:07:18,891 --> 00:07:23,096
When it comes to sensations in the body, you see, keep it very simple.

71
00:07:23,997 --> 00:07:26,560
Heat, itching, pain.

72
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:30,064
Don't start looking for the word like a poet might.

73
00:07:30,466 --> 00:07:31,406
You've lost the plot.

74
00:07:31,875 --> 00:07:54,492
all we're doing is just if the word doesn't come up then just use the word feeling because the attention should be riveted on just the sensation just sensation why just sensation because sensation happens only now

75
00:07:56,884 --> 00:07:58,507
You can't have a sensation yesterday.

76
00:07:59,047 --> 00:08:00,129
You can't have it last minute.

77
00:08:00,149 --> 00:08:01,050
You can't have it tomorrow.

78
00:08:01,189 --> 00:08:03,012
You're going to have a sensation right here and now.

79
00:08:03,713 --> 00:08:13,423
So the more that we're aware of sensation as a basic premise for our meditation, the more we're driving that intelligence into this present moment.

80
00:08:13,444 --> 00:08:16,547
And the more it locks into the present moment, the less it can think.

81
00:08:16,846 --> 00:08:18,668
Because thought is always an afterthought.

82
00:08:19,670 --> 00:08:23,535
You see something, you feel it, and then you say something.

83
00:08:23,555 --> 00:08:23,634
See?

84
00:08:24,307 --> 00:08:33,009
So to get that purity of intelligence, we need more and more to just bring that attention into the present moment, you see.

85
00:08:33,491 --> 00:08:35,196
Relaxing into the present moment.

86
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:38,163
But yet remaining alert.

87
00:08:39,341 --> 00:08:49,854
So, this noting word is part of the training of stopping a person living in thought, living in the mind.

88
00:08:50,715 --> 00:08:58,702
Now, some people find this very difficult because when they start noting, all they can be aware of is this word, rising, falling.

89
00:08:58,722 --> 00:08:59,924
They can't contact the brain.

90
00:08:59,945 --> 00:09:02,226
Just rising, it dominates the whole mind.

91
00:09:03,148 --> 00:09:04,168
See?

92
00:09:04,188 --> 00:09:09,315
Now, when that happens to somebody, what it's showing to that person is that they're living up here.

93
00:09:10,206 --> 00:09:12,229
They're living above the chin.

94
00:09:13,289 --> 00:09:16,833
They don't contact the body at all.

95
00:09:18,235 --> 00:09:24,201
People will say things like, yeah, I suffer anger, but I don't feel it.

96
00:09:24,302 --> 00:09:27,245
It's just in my head as a sort of angry thought, an angry dream.

97
00:09:29,307 --> 00:09:40,077
We lift ourselves up into this space, into this fantasy world, this virtual reality.

98
00:09:40,884 --> 00:09:48,697
and we've actually left the physical feelings, the actual feelings in the body, which are motivating all this stuff.

99
00:09:48,716 --> 00:09:53,023
So we have to reverse that process, we have to stop living in a fantasy world.

100
00:09:54,465 --> 00:10:07,904
So even though the word is, shall we say, for some people, flooding the whole of consciousness, that's all you can be aware of, this word, rising, falling, you see, keep guiding your attention to the sensation, and eventually it'll drop.

101
00:10:08,375 --> 00:10:17,777
As it drops and the word, as it were, recedes, you see, that's a sign to the meditator that they're coming off this never-never land.

102
00:10:20,844 --> 00:10:22,407
It's a very powerful technique.

103
00:10:23,269 --> 00:10:27,057
Now, at first, probably the whole weekend...

104
00:10:28,236 --> 00:10:31,682
There is just this effort to come back into the present moment.

105
00:10:32,063 --> 00:10:33,886
The mind wanders, you know where it is, you come back.

106
00:10:33,907 --> 00:10:35,789
The mind wanders, you know where it is, you come back.

107
00:10:36,331 --> 00:10:37,312
Now that's the practice.

108
00:10:37,732 --> 00:10:38,956
That's part of the course.

109
00:10:39,056 --> 00:10:40,918
You can't speed the course up.

110
00:10:41,220 --> 00:10:46,268
All that shows us is how restless we are.

111
00:10:46,688 --> 00:10:49,533
The Buddha compares it to a monkey, you see.

112
00:10:49,653 --> 00:10:51,898
The monkey mind, jumping from branch to branch.

113
00:10:54,544 --> 00:11:06,158
So the first part of the practice is to use the noting technique to just bring us slowly to the object, more and more into the present moment, just being aware of sensation, feeling sensation.

114
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:15,269
There comes a point, hopefully by tomorrow noon, where the mind begins to settle on the object.

115
00:11:15,418 --> 00:11:16,784
And it's not wandering off.

116
00:11:16,804 --> 00:11:21,365
It's actually staying still, at least, for a second or so.

117
00:11:21,384 --> 00:11:24,940
It's actually staying still on the sensation.

118
00:11:26,118 --> 00:11:35,366
Now, at this point, the meditator can say to themselves, ah, I've got it, this is it, concentration, I'm samadhi, I'm stuck right now, wonderful, I've collapsed into the present moment, it's marvelous, you see?

119
00:11:36,168 --> 00:11:37,068
And they stop noting.

120
00:11:37,469 --> 00:11:42,374
And of course, in their desperation, they find the mind immediately shoots off and goes all over the place.

121
00:11:42,715 --> 00:11:53,105
So, although we've matured the noting to a point where the mind is beginning to feel more still on the object, you have to keep going with it until it matures, you see?

122
00:11:53,586 --> 00:11:55,888
And there's a real feeling that...

123
00:11:55,868 --> 00:11:58,937
it's as though you can't take the mind off the object.

124
00:11:59,018 --> 00:11:59,921
It's really stuck there.

125
00:12:01,927 --> 00:12:03,231
Now that's the second stage.

126
00:12:03,732 --> 00:12:06,081
That's the second stage of the noting.

127
00:12:06,600 --> 00:12:16,791
One continues with that, you see, and for those of you who are, you know, mature in your meditation, you can find a point where you can drop it, you see.

128
00:12:16,811 --> 00:12:31,465
But the normal thing is to keep noting because at some point the concentration and the effort will so support that sense of knowing, that sense of intelligence, that sati, that awareness, that the noting will simply stop.

129
00:12:32,806 --> 00:12:35,629
And you'll just be there, as it were, with the object.

130
00:12:37,499 --> 00:12:45,548
So that's the growth of samadhi, that's the growth of concentration, supporting moment-to-moment awareness.

131
00:12:47,791 --> 00:12:58,984
And that's the purpose of using a noting, of using a word, you see, just to bring us to that.

132
00:13:15,855 --> 00:13:45,052
Now, once we've got this sort of moment-to-moment concentration on the breath, you see, mainly we do it on the breath, but of course, whenever something draws the attention, which may be a sensation in the body, a feeling of discomfort, a pain in the knee, whatever it is, or something coming from the emotional base, some feelings of heaviness, some depression, burning from anger, whatever, see?

133
00:13:46,432 --> 00:14:00,087
then that same consciousness, now more like a sort of laser beam, can move on to these objects, doesn't get caught up in them, doesn't allow them to slip up into this higher mentation and create fantasy.

134
00:14:02,551 --> 00:14:14,583
And in so doing, we directly experience an emotion as a physical mental feeling, not as a dream, not as a fantasy.

135
00:14:16,942 --> 00:14:20,447
In so doing, we become very intimate with it.

136
00:14:21,208 --> 00:14:23,150
And we're observing its qualities.

137
00:14:24,533 --> 00:14:26,174
The fact that it's just a process.

138
00:14:27,736 --> 00:14:31,162
The fact that it isn't an object or something substantial.

139
00:14:31,802 --> 00:14:36,008
It's like a blowing cloud just passing through the mind.

140
00:14:38,751 --> 00:14:41,414
And in so doing, we're not engaging it.

141
00:14:42,509 --> 00:14:47,554
When an emotion comes up, pleasant or unpleasant, we immediately form a relationship with it.

142
00:14:49,297 --> 00:14:56,807
Either we want to indulge it, and thereby we create a greater, greater state of that emotion.

143
00:14:57,366 --> 00:15:01,471
So if you want to get into revenge, before you know it, you've blown it up into a war.

144
00:15:02,394 --> 00:15:08,520
If you want to get into thinking about how you're going to get rich before you know it, it blows up into a book.

145
00:15:08,861 --> 00:15:09,241
You see?

146
00:15:11,062 --> 00:15:22,075
If you don't want to have something of course, if you don't want to feel the boredom, if you don't want to feel the depression, if you don't want to feel these sorts of things, then you push it down, you push it away, you turn your attention elsewhere, you don't want to see it.

147
00:15:22,556 --> 00:15:32,128
But all these actions of pushing away are simply more energy into that bad system, into that bad turbulence.

148
00:15:32,148 --> 00:15:35,652
But here in our meditation we take a very radical stance.

149
00:15:36,255 --> 00:15:39,721
It's a stance which doesn't occur to the self or the ego.

150
00:15:40,221 --> 00:15:42,624
The ego can only engage in the world.

151
00:15:42,684 --> 00:15:45,187
It can either indulge or suppress, push away.

152
00:15:46,249 --> 00:15:52,157
But here we find a consciousness which does neither and yet experiences things directly.

153
00:15:52,817 --> 00:15:53,578
See, that's a paradox.

154
00:15:54,559 --> 00:15:55,041
I think it is.

155
00:15:58,666 --> 00:16:07,173
So, by finding that position of the objective observer, we're just allowing these turbulences to arise and expend themselves.

156
00:16:08,875 --> 00:16:13,798
We're not pushing them away and therefore creating more bad energy, and we're not developing them.

157
00:16:13,999 --> 00:16:14,679
So what can they do?

158
00:16:15,559 --> 00:16:18,442
Because they need our will, they need our empowerment to grow.

159
00:16:21,465 --> 00:16:28,250
So, finding that position of the objective observer just allows the psychotherapy to continue.

160
00:16:29,091 --> 00:16:34,116
But like I say on the tape, you see, if you make that the object of your meditation then you're missing the point.

161
00:16:35,639 --> 00:16:39,101
What we really want to see is how we relate to these things.

162
00:16:44,648 --> 00:16:45,528
So that's the sitting.

163
00:16:53,296 --> 00:16:58,861
Now, to take that sort of moment to moment awareness throughout the day

164
00:17:00,479 --> 00:17:03,202
What the Mahasi asked people to do was to go very slow.

165
00:17:04,285 --> 00:17:07,730
Now, you know, the slower you go, the more you see.

166
00:17:08,892 --> 00:17:19,708
You know, if you see a film, for instance, these nature films, a frog's tongue or something, catching a fly, and it's slowed down, you know, so many thousands per second, then you can actually see the whole thing happen.

167
00:17:21,089 --> 00:17:26,117
So what we want to do is we want to really see what this psychophysical organism is doing.

168
00:17:26,679 --> 00:17:29,423
This is what I've been calling me all these years.

169
00:17:29,773 --> 00:17:35,019
And of course, the underlying reason is to find out why we're suffering.

170
00:17:37,721 --> 00:17:48,353
When the Buddha set off, when the Bodhisattva, as he was then, set off on his spiritual journey, the question wasn't, you know, how can I get rich?

171
00:17:49,334 --> 00:17:50,375
Or how can I be famous?

172
00:17:51,076 --> 00:17:55,140
Or, you know, how can I get blissful?

173
00:17:56,048 --> 00:17:58,269
It was, you know, what is the end of suffering?

174
00:17:58,490 --> 00:17:59,551
Is this it?

175
00:18:00,211 --> 00:18:02,034
You know, is human life about suffering?

176
00:18:02,634 --> 00:18:03,134
Full stop.

177
00:18:03,976 --> 00:18:08,121
Is it just carrying on and then you get sick and then you get old and you die?

178
00:18:08,161 --> 00:18:09,422
Or is there something else?

179
00:18:11,743 --> 00:18:16,108
So that's his search and that must be our search or else we're not actually doing his practice.

180
00:18:16,128 --> 00:18:16,950
We're doing something else.

181
00:18:19,531 --> 00:18:24,958
So our purpose is to really find out why suffering arises.

182
00:18:26,103 --> 00:18:27,325
What maintains it?

183
00:18:29,227 --> 00:18:32,090
So that investigation has to carry on all day.

184
00:18:32,131 --> 00:18:39,500
It has to carry on as a sort of background theme to the whole thing that we're trying to do.

185
00:18:39,801 --> 00:18:50,435
Trying to understand why we're suffering, why we're not in a state of satisfaction, why we can't get satisfaction in a sensual world, even though we may occasionally be happy with it.

186
00:18:52,159 --> 00:18:53,780
Why we can't do it as a constant thing.

187
00:18:56,916 --> 00:18:59,480
So going slow, like this walking meditation.

188
00:19:00,279 --> 00:19:02,702
In this walking meditation, you see, that's extremely slow.

189
00:19:03,042 --> 00:19:06,385
We don't have to go that slow all the time, but we need to go slow.

190
00:19:07,426 --> 00:19:08,288
Just take your time.

191
00:19:08,628 --> 00:19:12,172
So when we break from here, you see, don't leap up the stairs.

192
00:19:13,192 --> 00:19:13,492
Stop.

193
00:19:14,473 --> 00:19:16,435
Find yourself, take a breath, relax.

194
00:19:21,862 --> 00:19:23,143
And then start to climb.

195
00:19:23,241 --> 00:19:27,588
Lifting, placing, use the noting word just to stay with it.

196
00:19:31,273 --> 00:19:33,376
When you brush your teeth, you see, don't go mad.

197
00:19:34,298 --> 00:19:37,123
Take your time, stop.

198
00:19:38,365 --> 00:19:40,508
Note, intending to brush the teeth.

199
00:19:40,749 --> 00:19:41,849
Do it mindfully.

200
00:19:42,290 --> 00:19:45,695
You don't have to get dead slow, you'll never finish.

201
00:19:46,277 --> 00:19:49,501
But slow enough to actually be with what you're doing.

202
00:19:53,178 --> 00:19:55,119
When you open the door to your room, you see, just stop.

203
00:20:02,108 --> 00:20:03,349
Intending to open the door.

204
00:20:04,251 --> 00:20:04,432
See?

205
00:20:04,811 --> 00:20:05,292
Reaching.

206
00:20:06,233 --> 00:20:08,135
When you hold the handle, you see, feel it.

207
00:20:09,037 --> 00:20:09,478
Feel it.

208
00:20:10,118 --> 00:20:14,703
Feel what steel, what metal feels like.

209
00:20:15,144 --> 00:20:16,666
You get in contact with those feelings.

210
00:20:17,468 --> 00:20:18,269
Pressing, you see.

211
00:20:18,628 --> 00:20:19,130
Turning.

212
00:20:20,050 --> 00:20:21,732
You communicate with the spring.

213
00:20:23,401 --> 00:20:24,102
Don't attack it.

214
00:20:24,541 --> 00:20:25,884
Wow, bang, open the door.

215
00:20:26,104 --> 00:20:26,664
Crack.

216
00:20:26,684 --> 00:20:27,385
See?

217
00:20:27,405 --> 00:20:28,247
Can you feel it?

218
00:20:30,190 --> 00:20:30,750
Open the door.

219
00:20:31,030 --> 00:20:32,152
Close the door in the same way.

220
00:20:33,874 --> 00:20:33,994
See?

221
00:20:36,076 --> 00:20:40,563
So there's a constant effort just to be with what's actually happening at its base.

222
00:20:41,784 --> 00:20:42,144
Right?

223
00:20:42,164 --> 00:20:43,346
Don't try and get beyond it.

224
00:20:43,406 --> 00:20:46,570
Don't try and find out what is beyond consciousness.

225
00:20:46,730 --> 00:20:48,953
You're just trying to be with what's happening.

226
00:20:48,973 --> 00:20:50,496
Right here, right there and then.

227
00:20:52,198 --> 00:20:52,278
See?

228
00:20:52,298 --> 00:20:52,377
See?

229
00:20:53,471 --> 00:20:55,453
And you're trying to see your relationship to it.

230
00:20:55,473 --> 00:20:59,919
So you might close the door and somebody up the corridor, somebody next door, might bang the door.

231
00:21:01,220 --> 00:21:03,522
So then you notice irritation.

232
00:21:04,242 --> 00:21:08,387
Anger, anger.

233
00:21:08,428 --> 00:21:09,788
They die away.

234
00:21:13,853 --> 00:21:16,215
So take the slowness with you wherever you go.

235
00:21:16,536 --> 00:21:19,159
And every time you find yourself rushing, which you will do...

236
00:21:23,324 --> 00:21:27,069
And this is something that I shall urge you to take into your daily life.

237
00:21:27,089 --> 00:21:35,983
It's a very, very powerful technique just to stop all that agitation, all that accumulation throughout the day of all this emotional stuff.

238
00:21:38,007 --> 00:21:42,054
So you just stop, intend, and then do it.

239
00:21:42,473 --> 00:21:45,179
And when you come to the end of that action, be aware of it.

240
00:21:45,439 --> 00:21:46,740
That's been done, that's finished.

241
00:21:47,962 --> 00:21:48,262
Stop.

242
00:21:50,467 --> 00:21:50,547
See?

243
00:21:52,213 --> 00:21:53,576
Just bring yourself into the moment.

244
00:21:56,398 --> 00:21:56,940
Intention.

245
00:22:01,805 --> 00:22:05,430
So, those basically are your two techniques.

246
00:22:05,950 --> 00:22:11,696
Going slow, taking your time, relaxing, into the present moment, staying awake of course, yeah?

247
00:22:12,698 --> 00:22:14,000
And just keep the noting going.

248
00:22:14,640 --> 00:22:15,240
All the time.

249
00:22:16,162 --> 00:22:18,964
There's not supposed to be a time of the day when you stop noting.

250
00:22:20,446 --> 00:22:22,068
So that's the effort

251
00:22:22,218 --> 00:22:26,523
to keep that thinking mind steady on the object, not to let it move off it, you see.

252
00:22:31,109 --> 00:22:33,794
So now this isn't a sort of strenuous physical thing.

253
00:22:34,314 --> 00:22:37,317
This is not something that will exhaust you.

254
00:22:37,337 --> 00:22:48,292
This is something which actually contains our energy, so that by the end of the day you feel that you've really not wasted energy and that there's a lot of it around because it's not frazzled, you see.

